For the past several years I've been working on making VR shoes. Shoes you wear while playing a VR game that allow you to walk in the game but stay in the same spot in real life. Here I am walking in Half Life Alyx, fighting some antlions. I walk show walking backwards a few times in this clip.

* I'm using the joystick on the controller to move in game. I'll add feet tracking later for PCVR, maybe for the Oculus Quest too. 
* There are no motors in the shoes, they are passive. I've made motorized shoes in the past and will come back to that later. The passive shoes have stoppers on the front and back to stop the shoes when the user lifts his toes or heel.
* This is a DIY project and is open-source (see links below).
* It takes some practice to use them. I got the hang of walking in a few minutes. My wife in 20 minutes. It took a few hours to turn and walk simultaneously. As you can see I can walk backwards, but it still feels a bit awkward.
* You push against the climbing harness to bring your feet back. It's not the most natural walking feeling, but for me it's close enough and a ton of fun.
* Real-life audio captured with a microphone on the chair next to me.

